{{hatnote|Not to be confused with his contemporaries, the Nestorian patriarch [[Eliya I]], the Nestorian Bishop Eliya of Damascus, or the Nestorian Bishop Eliya of Mosul; with his predecessor the chronicler Eliya of Damascus; nor with the 15th-century Eliya who was bishop of Nisibis, Armenia, Mardin, Amid, Seert, and Hesna d'Kifa.}}

'''Elijah''',{{sfnp|Debié|2012|p=158}} '''Eliya''',<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GLIIAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland, ''New Ser., Vol. XII'' |location=London |publisher=Trübner & Co. |date=1880 |contribution=Proceedings of the Fifty-Seventh Anniversary Meeting of the Society |p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GLIIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR94 xciv] }}.</ref> or '''Elias of Nisibis'''{{sfnp|''Enc. Isl.''|2014}} (11{{nbsp}}February 975{{nbsp}}– 18{{nbsp}}July 1046) was a [[Nestorianism|Nestorian]] cleric who served as [[bishop of Beth Nuhadra]] (1002–1008) and [[archbishop of Nisibis]] (1008–1046). He has been called the most important Christian writer in Arabic—or even throughout non-Christian Asia{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}}—during the 11th century.{{sfnp|''Enc. Isl.''|2014}} He is best known for his ''Chronography'', which is an important source for the history of [[Sassanid Persia]].

==Name==
He shares the name of the [[Bible|Biblical]] [[Prophets in Judaism|prophet]] [[Elijah]] ({{lang-he|אֱלִיָּהוּ}}, ''Eliyahu''), whose name meant "My God is [[Jah]]".<ref>{{citation |title=New Bible Dictionary, ''2nd ed.'' |date=1982 |publisher=Tyndale Press |location=[[Wheaton, Illinois|Wheaton]] |isbn=0-8423-4667-8 |p=319 }}.</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Longman Pronunciation Dictionary |first=John C. |last=Wells |publisher= Longman |location=[[Harlow, England|Harlow]] |year=1990 |isbn= 0-582-05383-8 |page=239 |contribution=Elijah }}.</ref> The [[Syriac language|Syriac]] form of his name was Elīyā or Elīyāh. In [[Latinisation of names|Latin translation]], this became Elias.

He is usually distinguished as "Elijah of Nisibis" ({{lang-la|Elias Nisibenus}};{{sfn|''Enc. Iran.''|1998}} {{lang-ar|Illiyā al-Nasībī|script=Latn}}) from the location of his archbishopric. He is also known by the patronymic {{nowrap|'''Elijah Bar Shinajah'''}} ({{lang-syc|Elīyā bar Shīnāyā|script=Latn}}; {{lang-ar|Iliyyā ibn Šīnā|script=Latn}}),<ref name=sbd>{{citation |contribution=Elijah of Nisibis |contribution-url=http://syriaca.org/person/472 |title=A Guide to Syriac Authors |last=Walters |first=James E. |editor=David A. Michelson |editor2=Jeanne-Nicole Mellon St-Laurent |editor3=Nathan Gibson |editor4=Daniel Schwartz |display-editors=0 |date=2016 }}.</ref> meaning "Elijah, son of [[Shenna]]", in reference to the place of his birth.{{sfnp|''Enc. Isl.''|2014}}

==Life==
[[File:D501- vallée du petit zab à bechast. -L2-Ch 3.png|thumb|right|200px|The valley of the [[Little Zab]] in the 19th century.]]
[[File:Mar Jacob Church, Nisibis.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The ruins of the medieval [[Jacob of Nisibis|St{{nbsp}}Jacob]] Cathedral in present-day [[Nusaybin]], [[Turkey]].]]
Elijah was born in [[Shenna]], just south of the [[Little Zab River|Little Zab]]'s confluence with the [[Tigris River|Tigris]]{{sfnp|''Enc. Isl.''|2014}} (near present-day [[Al-Zab]], [[Iraq]]) on 11 February 975.{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}}

On Sunday, 15{{nbsp}}September 994, he was [[ordination|ordained]] as a priest at the monastery of Mar Shemʿon by Yohannes, [[archbishop of Fars]] and [[bishop of Shenna]].{{sfn|''Chronography''|loc=i. 112}} He studied throughout northern [[Mesopotamia]], including [[Mosul]].{{sfnp|Griffith|1996|p=122}}

On Sunday, 15{{nbsp}}February 1002, he was [[consecration|consecrated]] [[bishop of Beth Nuhadra]] (present-day [[Dohuk]], [[Iraq]]) by Yohannan, who had become the [[List of Patriarchs of the Church of the East|Nestorian patriarch]] in 1000{{sfn|''Chronography''|loc=i. 112}} by appealing directly to the [[Abbasid Empire|Abbasid]] governor at [[Shiraz]] without regard to the usual election procedures.<ref>[[Bar Hebraeus]], ''Ecclesiastical Chronicle'' ({{abbr|ed|edited by}}.{{nbsp}}Abeloos & al.), ii. 260–2.</ref>

On Sunday, 26{{nbsp}}December 1008, he succeeded Yahballaha as [[archbishop of Nisibis]] (present-day [[Nusaybin]], [[Turkey]]).{{sfn|''Chronography''|loc=i. 112}}{{sfn|''Chronography''|loc=i. 110}}

From 15–29 July 1026, he paid a series of visits—the "Seven Sessions"—to the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] [[vizier]] [[Abu'l-Qasim al-Husayn ibn Ali al-Maghribi]] to discuss Christian doctrines and other topics.{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}} Additional meetings between the two were held in December 1026 and June 1027.{{sfnp|Griffith|1996|p=122}} Three letters—two by Elijah and one by the vizier—are preserved from their correspondence the following year, showing their continuing good relations.{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}}

He died on 18 July 1046 at [[Mayyafariqin]].{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}}

==Works==
{{anchor|Chronography}}

===''Chronography''===
Elijah is best known for his ''Chronography'' or ''Chronology'' ({{lang-ar|Kitāb al-Azmina|script=Latn}}; {{lang-la|Opus Chronologicum}}), which forms an important source concerning the history of [[Sassanid Persia]].{{sfn|''Enc. Iran.''|1998}} It is divided into two sections, a [[chronicle]] modeled after [[Eusebius]]'s ''[[Church History (Eusebius)|Ecclesiastical History]]'' and a treatment of calendars and calendrical calculations. It is exceptional among Syriac chronicles for the large amount of civil history Elijah included among his ecclesiastical notices.{{sfnp|Debié|2012|p=167}} The chronicle includes separate lists of the [[Sassanid dynasty]] (after the lost 7th-century work of [[James of Edessa]]) and the [[patriarchs of Seleucia]]{{sfn|''Chronography''|loc=vii. 42&nbsp;ff}} (after the lost 5th-century work of [[Annianus of Alexandria]]).{{sfnp|Mosshammer|2008|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=0umDqPOf2L8C&pg=PA359 359]}} The [[list of popes|popes]] and [[patriarch|other patriarch]]s are included in the general annals which begin during the reign of the [[list of Roman emperors|Roman emperor]] [[Tiberius]] and end with the year 1018.{{sfn|''Chronography|loc=vii. 73&nbsp;ff}} His treatment of calendrical systems has tables for computation of the [[Syriac new year|Syriac]] and [[Persian new year]]s and includes several [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] calendars, along with their feasts and holidays. As seen, many of Elijah's own sources, which he thoroughly documents, have now been lost and his own work is preserved in only a single [[manuscript]],<ref>[[British Library]] Add. MS 7197.</ref>{{efn|A brief section of Elijah's work is also quoted in a separate manuscript.<ref>[[Königliche Bibliothek]] MS 102.</ref>}} which fortunately includes few [[Lacuna (manuscripts)|omissions]].{{efn|The principal [[Lacuna (manuscripts)|lacunae]] are four [[folio]]s covering the years 785–878 and one [[folio]] covering the years 971–994.{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}}}} The manuscript is in [[Syriac language|Syriac]], with most paragraphs in the first section followed by an [[Arabic language|Arabic]] translation.{{sfn|''Enc. Iran.''|1998}}{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}} The ''Chronography'' was the last East Syrian text to be written in Syriac.{{sfnp|Debié|2012|p=158}}

There have been two published editions of the work:
* {{citation |editor-last=Delaporte |editor-first=L.-J. |author=Elijah of Nisibis |display-authors=0 |url=https://archive.org/stream/LaChronographieDelieBarShinaya/DelaporteLaChronographieDelieBarShinaya#page/n7/mode/1up |date=1910 |title=La Chronographie d'Élie Bar-Šinaya, Métropolitain de Nisibe |location=Paris |publisher=Librairie Honoré Champion |series=''Bibliothèque de l'École des Hautes Études, ''Vol. 181'' }}. {{fr icon}}
* {{citation |editor-last=Brooks |editor-first=E.W. |editor2=I.-B. Chabot |display-editors=1 |author=Elijah of Nisibis |display-authors=0 |url=https://archive.org/stream/OpusChronologicumByEliasBishopOfNisibis/BrooksEliaeMetropolitaeNisibeniOpusChronologicumPt1syriacss37#page/n0/mode/2up |date=1909–1910 |series=''Corpus Scriptorum Christianorum Orientalium: Scriptores Syri Textus, ''3rd Ser., Vol. VII'' |title=Opus Chronologicum |location=Rome, Paris, &c. }}. {{la icon}}{{nbsp}}& {{syc icon}}

{{anchor|Book of Sessions}}

===''Book of Sessions''===
Elijah's ''Book of Sessions'' or ''Dialogues''<ref name=diez/> ({{lang-ar|Kitāb al-Majālis|script=Latn}}) claims to relate his conversations during his seven visits to the [[Abbasid Empire|Abbasid]] [[vizier]] [[Abu'l-Qasim al-Husayn ibn Ali al-Maghribi]].<ref>{{citation |last=Bertaina |first=David |pp=197–207 |title=Islam and Christian–Muslim Relations, ''Vol. 22, No. 2'' |date=2011 |contribution=Science, Syntax, and Superiority in Eleventh-Century Christian–Muslim Discussion: Elias of Nisibis on the Arabic and Syriac Languages }}.</ref> Dedicated to the "honorable, believing, elder brother" Abu al-ʿAla Saʿid ibn Sahl al-Katib, the work is intended as a literary apologetic as much as record of the events of the seven meetings, with its epilogue including the [[imprimatur]] of the patriarchal secretary Abu al-Faraj ʿAbd Allah ibn at-Tayyib.{{sfnp|Griffiths|1999|p=49}} In order, the chapters cover:{{sfnp|Griffiths|1999|p=50}}

* [[God in Christianity|God]]'s [[monotheism|unity]] and [[Christian Trinity|trinity]]
* [[Jesus]]'s [[incarnation (Christianity)|incarnation]] of [[Christology|divine and human nature]]s
* [[Quran]]ic support for considering some forms{{sfnp|Griffiths|1999|p=51}} of Christianity as a monotheistic religion
* [[Logic]]al and [[miracle|miraculous]] justifications for various [[Christian doctrine]]s
* Elijah's own profession of monotheism
* [[Linguistics|Language]] and considerations of its importance in [[theology]]
* Christian perspectives on [[astrology]], [[Islam]], and the [[soul]]

According to Elijah's account, the vizier asking for the meetings after he had experienced a miraculous cure at the hands of a Christian monk, causing him to reconsider his previous understanding of their faith as polytheistic and unfaithful to God.{{sfnp|Griffiths|1999|p=50}} It is particularly remembered for its statement of Christian monotheism in trinity in its 5th dialogue.<ref name=diez>{{citation |last=Diez |first=Martino |contribution=The Vizier and the Bishop Face to Face about the Trinity |date=December 2015 |title=Oasis, ''No. 22'' |pp=98–112 |location=Venice |publisher=Marcianum Press }}.</ref>

A full [[critical edition]] of the Book of Sessions along with the correspondence between Elijah and Abu'l-Qasim al-Maghribi was published by Nikolai N. Seleznyov.<ref>Seleznyov, Nikolai N., Kitāb al-majālis li-mār ʾIliyyā, muṭrān Niṣībīn, wa-risālatuh ilā ʾl-wazīr al-kāmil Abī ʾl-Qāsim al-Ḥusayn ibn ʿAlī ʾl-Maġribī. Kniga sobesedovaniĭ Ilii, mitropolita Nisivina, c vezirom Abū-l-Ḳāsimom al-Ḥusaĭnom ibn ʿAlī al-Maġribī i Poslanie mitropolita Ilii veziru Abū-l-Ḳāsimu. [https://archive.org/details/SeleznyovLiberSessionum Book of Sessions by Mar Elias (ʾIliyyā), Metropolitan of Nisibis], with Wazir Abū ʾl-Qāsim al-Ḥusayn ibn ʿAlī al-Maghribī and the Epistle of Metropolitan Elias (ʾIliyyā) to Wazir Abū ʾl-Qāsim]. Moscow, Russia : Grifon, 1439 Anno Hegirae [=2017/8 CE]. {{ISBN|9785988623670}}, 9785988623663.</ref>

===Other works===
[[File:The Book of the Interpreter WDL7083.pdf|thumb|200px|right|A 1524 manuscript edition of Elijah's ''Book of the Interpreter''.]]
Elijah also composed other theological and scholarly works.

He wrote defenses of [[Nestorianism]] against both [[Islam]] and other [[Christian denominations]] and treatises on Syrian [[canon law]], [[asceticism]], and [[ethics]]. His guide to "rational management" of anxiety ({{lang-ar|Kitāb dafʾ al-Hamm|script=Latn}}) is also dedicated to the Abbasid vizier, whom he claims requested such a book during their sessions together. It advocates cultivating a general thankfulness; treatment of general anxiety through the religious virtues of piety, gratitude, chastity, humility, mercy, and repentance; and treatment of specific anxieties through the philosophical virtues of seeking advice, behaving well, and being generous, just, and forgiving.{{sfnp|Griffith|1996|p=123}} His "Letter on the Unity of the Creator and Trinity of His Hypotases" ({{lang-ar|Risāla Fī Wahdāniyyat al-Khāliq wa-Tathlīth Aqānīmihi|script=Latn}}) states the arguments for [[trinitarianism]] for a curious Islamic judge.{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}} His "Letter on the Merit of Chastity" ({{lang-ar|Risāla fī Fadīlat al-ʿAfāf|script=Latn}}) attempts to refute [[Muʿtazilī al-Jāhiz]]'s ({{abbr|d|died}}. 869) arguments in favor of physical pleasure.{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}}

He also composed a [[Syriac language|Syriac]] grammar and a Syriac–Arabic dictionary,{{sfn|''EI''|1998}} ''The Book of the Interpreter'' ({{lang-syc|ܟܬܐܒ ܐܠܬܪܓܡܐܢ}}; {{lang-ar|Kitāb at-Targumān|script=Latn}}). Because a standard [[Arabic script]] had not yet developed, the Arabic sections of the book were written using [[Garshuni]], a transliteration of Arabic into the [[Syriac alphabet]].<ref>{{citation |contribution-url=https://www.wdl.org/en/item/7083/ |contribution=The Book of the Interpreter |date=2012 |publisher=World Digital Library |url=https://www.wdl.org/en/search/?institution=syriac-orthodox-archdiocese-of-aleppo |title=Syriac-Orthodox Archdiocese of Aleppo }}.</ref> The work was further translated into [[Latin]] by [[Thomas Obicini]] as his 1636 ''{{lang|la|Thesaurus Arabico-Syro-Latinus}}''.<ref>{{citation |last=Obicini |first=Thomas |authorlink=Thomas Obicini |editor=Dominicus Germanicus |date=1636 |url=https://archive.org/details/ThesaurusArabico-syro-latinus |title=Thesaurus Arabico-Syro-Latinus |location=Rome |publisher=Holy Congregation for the Propagation of the Faith }}. {{la icon}}, {{ar icon}},{{nbsp}}& {{syc icon}}</ref>

Editions of these works include:
{{expand list|date=January 2017}}
* {{citation |author=Elijah of Nisibis |display-authors=0 |editor-last=Gottheil |editor-first=Richard J.H. |title=A Treatise on Syriac Grammar |date=1887 |location=Berlin }}.
* {{citation |author=Elijah of Nisibis |editor-last=Horst |editor-first=L. |display-authors=0 |title=Des Metropolitan Elias von Nisibis Buch vom Beweis der Wahrheit des Glaubens |date=2012 |series=''Syriac Studies Library'', No. 123 |publisher=Gorgias Press }}. {{de icon}}

==Legacy==
In addition to Elijah's importance to [[Persian history]] and for his preservation of passages of otherwise lost ancient and medieval authors,{{sfn|''Enc. Iran.''|1998}} he became famed throughout the Islamic world for his studious method and wide-ranging expertise in [[Christian theology|Christian]] and [[Islamic theology]], [[philology|language and literature]], [[philosophy]], [[medicine]], and [[mathematics]].{{sfnp|''CMR''|2010}}

