'''Herbert Allen Giles''' (8 December 1845{{snd}}13 February 1935) was a British diplomat and [[sinologist]] who was the [[Joseph Needham Professor of Chinese History, Science, and Civilization|professor of Chinese]] at [[Cambridge University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Vol_6/Table_of_contributors |title=Table of contributors |work=Encyclopædia Britannica, 1911}}</ref> for 35 years. Giles was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] before becoming a British diplomat in China. He modified a [[Mandarin Chinese]] [[romanisation]] system established by [[Thomas Francis Wade|Thomas Wade]], resulting in the widely known [[Wade–Giles]] Chinese romanisation system. Among his many works were translations of the ''[[Analects of Confucius]]'', the ''[[Dao De Jing|Lao Tzu (Tao Te Ching)]]'', the ''[[Zhuangzi (book)| Chuang Tzu]]'', and, in 1892, the widely published ''[[A Chinese-English Dictionary]]''.

==Biography==
Herbert A. Giles was the fourth son of [[John Allen Giles]] (1808–1884), an [[Anglican]] clergyman. After studying at [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]], Herbert became a British diplomat to [[Qing dynasty|Qing China]], serving from 1867 to 1892.  He also spent several years (1885–1888) at [[Fort Santo Domingo]] in [[Tamsui]], northern [[Taiwan under Qing rule|Taiwan]]. He was the father of Bertram, Valentine, Lancelot, Edith, Mable, and [[Lionel Giles]]. In 1897 Herbert Giles became only the second [[Joseph Needham Professorship of Chinese History, Science, and Civilization|professor of Chinese language]] appointed at the [[University of Cambridge]], succeeding [[Thomas Francis Wade|Thomas Wade]].<ref>{{acad|id=GLS932HA|name=Giles, Herbert Allen}}</ref> At the time of his appointment, there were no other sinologists at Cambridge. Giles was therefore free to spend most of his time among the ancient Chinese texts earlier donated by Wade, publishing what he chose to translate from his eclectic reading in Chinese literature.<ref>Aylmer, Charles, East Asian History 13–14, 1997, pp. 1–7; Sterckx, Roel, ''In the Fields of Shennong: An inaugural lecture delivered before the University of Cambridge on 30 September 2008 to mark the establishment of the Joseph Needham Professorship of Chinese History, Science and Civilization''. Cambridge: Needham Research Institute, 2008.</ref>

His later works include a history of the Chinese Pictorial Art in 1905<ref>{{cite journal|title=''An Introduction to the History of Chinese Pictorial Art'' by Herbert A. Giles|journal=The Burlington Magazine for Connoisseurs|date=August 1905|volume=7|issue=29|page=405|jstor=856445}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chavannes|first=Ed.|title=''An Introduction to the History of Chinese Pictorial Art'' by H. A. Giles|journal=T'oung Pao|year=1905|volume=6|series=Second Series|issue=2|page=251|jstor=4525813}}</ref> and his 1914 [[Hibbert Lectures]] on [[Confucianism]] which was published in 1915 by [[Williams and Norgate]] ([[:de:Williams & Norgate|de]]).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Giles|first1=Herbert A.|title=Confucianism and Its Rivals|journal=[[The Journal of Race Development]]|date=January 1916|volume=6|issue=3|page=350|jstor=29738158|doi=10.2307/29738158}}</ref> He dedicated the third edition of ''[[Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio]]'' (1916) to his seven grandchildren, but at the end of his life was on speaking terms with only one of his surviving children. An ardent agnostic, he was also an enthusiastic [[freemason]]. He never became a [[Fellow]] at one of the constituent colleges of the University of Cambridge, despite being a university professor for 35 years. He finally retired in 1932, and died at 89

==Legacy==
Giles received the [[Prix Julien]] award from the [[French Academy]] in 1897 for his ''[https://archive.org/details/chinesebiodictionary00gileuoft Chinese Biographical Dictionary]''.<ref name="Schlegel">{{cite journal|last=Schlegel|first=G.|authorlink=Gustaaf Schlegel|title=古今姓氏族譜, ''A Chinese Biographical Dictionary'' by Herbert A. Giles|journal=T'oung Pao|year=1897|volume=8|issue=4|pages=438–441|jstor=4525305}}</ref> Generally considered unreliable among modern academics,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kennedy|first=George A.|title=Dates in Giles' Biographical Dictionary|journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society|date=July–September 1950|volume=70|issue=3|pages=188–189|jstor=596269|doi=10.2307/596269}}</ref> [[Endymion Wilkinson]] described it as:

{{quote|full of inaccuracies and the selection leaves much to be desired. Between one third and a half of the dates are wrong because Giles supposed that if somebody is recorded as having died in 1200 aged 63 he or she must have been born in 1137 (in most cases 1138 would have been a better guess).<ref name="Wilkinson2000">{{cite book|author=Endymion Wilkinson|authorlink=Endymion Wilkinson|title=Chinese History: A Manual|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ERnrQq0bsPYC&pg=157|year=2000|publisher=[[Harvard University Asia Center]]|isbn=978-0-674-00249-4|pages=157}}</ref>}}

He also ran afoul of the Chinese scholar [[Gu Hongming]], who declared {{quote|Dr. Giles' Chinese biographical dictionary, it must be admitted, is a work of immense labour. But here again Dr. Giles shows an utter lack of the most ordinary judgment. In such a work, one would expect to find notices only of really notable men.}} Nor did Gu appreciate Giles' great ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=l3EgAQAAMAAJ Chinese-English Dictionary]'' describing it as {{quote| ... in no sense a dictionary at all. It is merely a collection of Chinese phrases and sentences, translated by Dr. Giles without any attempt at selection, arrangement, order or method," and "decidedly of less value than even [[Samuel Wells Williams|the old dictionary]] of Dr. Williams."<ref>"A Great Sinologue," in  ''[[s:Page:The Spirit of the Chinese People.djvu/166|The Spirit of the Chinese People]]'' [[Wikisource]]</ref>}}

In 1917, he funded an award, the [[Prix Giles]], in the amount of eight hundred francs. Administered by the [[Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres]], it is given every two years to a French person who has written a work about China, Japan, or East Asia, in general <ref>[http://www.persee.fr/doc/crai_0065-0536_1917_num_61_1_88048 Comptes rendus des séances de l'Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres, 61ᵉ année, N. 1, 1917. p. 20]</ref>.

